ROMAN_NUMERAL

NORMALISED EXTRACT

Functions and behavior

1) toRoman(n)
- Purpose: Convert an integer in the inclusive range 1..3999 to a Roman numeral using standard subtractive notation.
- Signature: toRoman(n)
  - Input: n (integer)
  - Output: string (Roman numeral)
  - Errors: Throws TypeError if input is not an integer. Throws RangeError if input is outside 1..3999.
- Core algorithm:
  - Values array in descending order: [1000, 900, 500, 400, 100, 90, 50, 40, 10, 9, 5, 4, 1]
  - Symbols array mapped 1:1 to values: ["M","CM","D","CD","C","XC","L","XL","X","IX","V","IV","I"]
  - Greedy construction: iterate from largest to smallest value, compute times = floor(n / values[i]), append symbols[i] repeated times to result, subtract values[i] * times from n, proceed until n == 0.
  - Complexity: O(k) where k is number of symbol types (constant); effectively O(1) for bounded n.

2) fromRoman(s, options = {})
- Purpose: Convert a Roman numeral string to an integer supporting strict validation and an optional lenient preprocessing mode.
- Signature: fromRoman(s, options = {})
  - Input: s (string), options (object) with optional properties: lenient (boolean, default false), normalize (boolean, default true)
  - Output: integer (numeric value of the Roman numeral)
  - Errors: Throws TypeError when input is not a string or when string contains invalid characters or empty after normalization; throws TypeError when numeral fails strict pattern validation.
- Preprocessing and validation behavior:
  - normalize (default true): trim input and remove all internal whitespace via replace(/\s+/g, "").
  - Strict mode (lenient: false): trim, uppercase, then validate using strict Roman regex for 1..3999.
  - Lenient mode (lenient: true): uppercase, ensure contains only Roman letters via /^[IVXLCDM]+$/, then apply narrow replacements: IIII -> IV, XXXX -> XL, CCCC -> CD, to accept some additive/clock forms while remaining safe.
- Strict Roman numeral validation regex (enforces 1..3999): ^M{0,3}(CM|CD|D?C{0,3})(XC|XL|L?X{0,3})(IX|IV|V?I{0,3})$
- Conversion algorithm after validation:
  - Map single-letter values: {I:1, V:5, X:10, L:50, C:100, D:500, M:1000}
  - Iterate characters left-to-right, for each character value lookahead to next; if next > current, add (next - current) and skip next by advancing index an extra step; otherwise add current.
  - Resulting integer will be in range 1..3999 (guaranteed by prior regex validation).

