BEST PRACTICES

- Always call toRoman with validated integers; prefer try/catch around toRoman when dealing with external input.
- Prefer fromRoman with normalize: true to accept user input containing whitespace; use lenient: true only when needing to accept additive or clock-style numerals and after documenting the narrow replacements.
- Avoid relying on lenient mode for security-critical parsing: lenient mode performs limited transformations only; it still rejects non-Roman characters.
- For round-trip checks (toRoman followed by fromRoman), use normalize=true and lenient=false to ensure strict equality and predictability.

TROUBLESHOOTING

- Symptom: fromRoman throws invalid Roman numeral string for common inputs like "iiii" or "xxxx".
  - Cause: strict mode rejects additive forms. Fix: enable options.lenient = true, which will normalize IIII->IV, XXXX->XL, CCCC->CD before strict regex validation.
- Symptom: toRoman throws RangeError for input 0 or 4000.
  - Cause: numeric limits are 1..3999. Fix: validate numeric domain before calling, or map values outside domain to an error-handling path.
- Symptom: fromRoman returns unexpected value when input contains spaces.
  - Cause: normalize option may have been disabled. Fix: call fromRoman(s, { normalize: true }).

